  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C2_232_nominalization_in_essays",
  "title": "C2.232 Nominalization in Essays — Grammar of Abstraction and Authority",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English essays, we turn verbs into nouns for formality: 'The development of technology,' 'The reduction of waste.' Spanish does the same through **nominalization**, often even more elegantly. *El desarrollo de la tecnología,* *La reducción de residuos.* English uses this structure to sound objective; Spanish uses it to sound **balanced and authoritative**. English creates abstraction through vocabulary; Spanish does it through syntax—turning motion into concept, and concept into structure."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What nominalization does:**\nNominalization turns a verb or adjective into a noun, making ideas sound formal, general, or analytical. It allows academic Spanish to discuss processes as concepts rather than actions.\n\n**2️⃣ Common endings and meanings:**\n| Ending | Source | Example | Function |\n|---------|----------|----------|-----------|\n| -ción | verbs ending in -ar/-er | *educar → educación* | acts or results (education) |\n| -miento | verbs | *construir → conocimiento* | process / product |\n| -dad / -tad | adjectives | *libre → libertad* | qualities (freedom) |\n| -eza | adjectives | *triste → tristeza* | states (sadness) |\n| -ura | adjectives | *seguro → seguridad* | abstract properties |\n\n**3️⃣ Syntax and placement:**\nNominalized phrases often start with a definite article (*el, la, los, las*) and pair with *de* + noun to describe scope or topic:\n- *El análisis de los datos muestra patrones claros.*\n- *La expansión de las ciudades afecta el medio ambiente.*\n\n**4️⃣ Verb choice around nominalization:**\nAcademic Spanish favors verbs like *implicar, suponer, representar, favorecer,* to build connection without personal tone.\n- *La investigación implica una revisión constante.*\n- *El avance representa un cambio significativo.*\n\n**5️⃣ Why use it:**\nNominalization turns verbs into arguments. It depersonalizes writing, allowing ideas to stand independent of the author’s opinion.\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen English uses “-tion,” “-ment,” or “-ness,” look for *-ción, -miento, -dad* in Spanish. Use it to write about systems, trends, or theories—not people."
