  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, words like 'well,' 'so,' or 'you know' soften or steer conversation. Spanish uses its own **pragmatic particles**—small words that carry tone, intention, or attitude. *Pues, ya, hombre, bueno, entonces, mira.* They rarely translate directly. *Ya* can mean 'already,' 'now,' or 'enough' depending on rhythm. *Pues* can start a thought or concede defeat. English fills silence with gestures; Spanish fills it with **particles**—tiny grammar tools that shape the air between sentences."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What pragmatic particles do:**\nThey regulate conversation rather than describe it. Spanish uses them to mark agreement, hesitation, impatience, or transition.\n\n**2️⃣ Common particles and their functions:**\n| Particle | Literal Meaning | Function | Example |\n|-----------|------------------|-----------|----------|\n| *ya* | already / now | finality or insistence | *¡Ya basta!* (Enough already!) |\n| *pues* | well / then | hesitation, linking, or softening | *Pues… no sé.* (Well… I don’t know.) |\n| *hombre* | man | empathy, disbelief, or emphasis | *¡Hombre, claro!* (Of course, man!) |\n| *bueno* | good / well | transition or concession | *Bueno, seguimos.* (Well, let’s continue.) |\n| *entonces* | then / so | consequence or shift | *Entonces, ¿qué hacemos?* (So, what do we do?) |\n| *mira / oye* | look / listen | attention-getter | *Mira, te explico.* (Look, I’ll explain.) |\n| *vale* (Spain) | okay / alright | agreement | *Vale, perfecto.* (Alright, perfect.) |\n| *ya ves / fíjate* | you see / notice | empathy or persuasion | *Ya ves cómo es.* (You see how he is.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Rhythm and placement:**\n- Particles often appear at **beginnings or ends** of clauses, where tone naturally rises or falls.\n  - *Pues sí.* / *Sí, hombre.* / *Bueno, ya veremos.*\n- In writing, commas mark their pause value; in speech, tone carries their meaning.\n\n**4️⃣ Regional and stylistic notes:**\n| Region | Signature Particle | Example |\n|--------|--------------------|----------|\n| Spain | *vale, venga, hombre* | *¡Venga, vamos!* |\n| Mexico | *ándale, órale, ya* | *¡Ándale, qué bien!* |\n| Caribbean | *pues nada, oye* | *Pues nada, nos vemos.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nParticles never change grammar—but they transform meaning. They are emotional punctuation marks, creating flow, humor, or gentleness in everyday speech."
