    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What dialectal constructions are:**\nThey’re regional grammatical patterns that diverge from the 'standard' without losing coherence or identity. Each region favors different verb tenses, pronouns, and syntax for rhythm, emphasis, or cultural style.\n\n**2️⃣ Core structural differences:**\n| Region | Construction | Example | Function |\n|--------|---------------|----------|-----------|\n| River Plate (Argentina, Uruguay) | *voseo* verbs | *Vos sabés, vos podés* | Familiar tone; replaces *tú* forms. |\n| Caribbean (Cuba, Puerto Rico, DR) | subject after verb | *Llegó ella* (She arrived) | Keeps rhythm; mirrors oral cadence. |\n| Mexico / Central America | aspect preference | *Andaba diciendo que...* | Continuous or habitual tone. |\n| Andean | subjunctive overuse | *Espero que venga* instead of *viniera* | Adds immediacy; emotional tone. |\n| Spain (north) | double negatives and clitics | *No lo sé nada* (nonstandard but local) | Emphasis, speech pattern. |\n\n**3️⃣ Pronoun flexibility:**\n- *Vosotros* (Spain only) vs. *ustedes* (Latin America) for plural 'you'.\n- Object pronoun shifts: *leísmo* (*Le vi* instead of *Lo vi*) common in central Spain.\n- *Loísmo / laísmo* (using *lo/la* for people) appears in casual Castilian and rural speech.\n\n**4️⃣ Tense and rhythm:**\n| Construction | Region | Example |\n|---------------|---------|----------|\n| Future with *ir a* replaces simple future | Latin America | *Voy a hacerlo mañana.* |\n| Perfect used as simple past | Spain | *He comido hoy.* (I ate today.) |\n| Simple past replaces perfect | Latin America | *Comí hoy.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nEach construction marks not ignorance but belonging. To understand dialects, listen to **pattern, not deviation**—each region bends rules for identity and music."
