  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_C2_240_grammar_of_truth",
  "title": "C2.240 Grammar of Truth — The Final Layer of Mastery",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we talk about truth as content—something to tell, prove, or hide. Spanish treats truth as **tone**—something to reveal through how one speaks, not just what one says. *Es verdad,* *la verdad es que,* *según dicen,* *se dice que.* English separates truth from speech; Spanish fuses them through grammar. The way you conjugate, the mood you choose, the distance you hold—all reveal how much of the truth you believe. English states truth; Spanish *weighs* it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The mechanics of expressing truth:**\nSpanish grammar encodes degrees of belief through **mood, aspect, and impersonal form.** Truth is grammatical, not absolute.\n\n**2️⃣ The indicative — asserted truth:**\nUsed for facts, conviction, or clarity.\n- *Sé que vendrá.* (I know he will come.)\n- *Es cierto que miente.* (It’s true he lies.)\nThe indicative claims truth as stable.\n\n**3️⃣ The subjunctive — questioned or subjective truth:**\nUsed for uncertainty, emotion, or respectful distance.\n- *No creo que venga.* (I don’t think he’s coming.)\n- *Aunque sea verdad, no importa.* (Even if it’s true, it doesn’t matter.)\nThe subjunctive protects truth from arrogance.\n\n**4️⃣ The conditional — reflective or moral truth:**\nUsed for introspection or judgment.\n- *Diría que es justo.* (I’d say it’s fair.)\n- *Podría ser verdad.* (It could be true.)\nThe conditional introduces humility into certainty.\n\n**5️⃣ The impersonal — communal or ethical truth:**\nSpanish often dissolves the speaker entirely to make truth collective:\n- *Se dice que el tiempo cura todo.* (They say time heals everything.)\n- *Se sabe que el silencio pesa más que las palabras.* (It’s known that silence weighs more than words.)\n\n**6️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIn Spanish, grammar doesn’t just tell you what’s true—it tells you how truth feels to the speaker. Mood is philosophy made verbal."
    },
